Matt, thank you for such a thoughtful question.

I am familiar with both Lakoff and Johnson's work and Whitehead's notion of prehension, and I think you're identifying a genuine tension in the language.

My use of "compute" is deliberate, but not in the conventional sense of symbolic manipulation performed by an external machine. In Multiplicity, computation is intended as a primitive relational process rather than an operation carried out by a separate observer on a separate object.

In that respect, my use of "compute" is actually closer to Whitehead's prehension than to classical information processing. Every entity is continually integrating, constraining, and transforming its relations with other entities. What Whitehead describes as prehension, I would describe as recursive computation. The difference is largely one of emphasis.

Whitehead begins from experience and asks how reality becomes. I begin from relational recursion and ask how stable structures, observers, and experiences emerge. The underlying process may be describing much the same territory from different directions.

Your point about metaphorical load is well taken. "Prehension" carries embodied, phenomenological implications of grasping, feeling, and participation. "Compute" carries modern associations of discreteness, formalism, and machine logic. I chose "compute" partly because I wanted a term capable of spanning physical, mathematical, biological, cognitive, and social processes under a single operational description.

That said, I do not mean computation as the manipulation of pre-existing symbols. I mean the ongoing generation of structure through recursive relational interaction. In that sense, computation is not something happening within reality; it is what reality is doing.

One way to put it is that prehension emphasizes the experiential aspect of relation, while computation emphasizes the transformational aspect of relation. Multiplicity attempts to model both, but my vocabulary has tended to foreground the latter because I am seeking a formal framework that can be mathematically specified and experimentally constrained.

So I would not say that "compute" replaces "prehend." Rather, I would say that prehension may be one manifestation of a more general recursive process that Multiplicity describes as computation.

Your observation is valuable, though, because it raises the possibility that the framework may benefit from distinguishing between computational recursion as the formal mechanism and prehensive participation as its phenomenological expression.

This reply does two useful things: it acknowledges the Lakoff/Johnson critique rather than dismissing it, and it reframes "compute" as a broader ontological process instead of a machine metaphor, bringing it into closer alignment with Whitehead without surrendering the mathematical ambitions of Multiplicity.

