Matt, I have thought quite a bit about the metaphorical load that "compute" carries, and I think the reason I continue to use it comes from a deeper commitment within Multiplicity itself.

One of the foundational inspirations for the framework is a generalized reading of the Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic. In mathematics, every integer can be uniquely decomposed into primes. Multiplicity takes that insight seriously not merely as a mathematical law but as a possible principle of reality more generally.

In that context, primes are not important because they are numbers. They are important because they are irreducible. They represent elements that cannot be reduced further within a given system.

The claim is not that reality is literally made of prime numbers. Rather, reality appears to be composed of irreducible constituents whose interactions generate all higher-order structures. Whether those constituents are particles, processes, relations, events, or something else remains an open question.

This is where computation enters the picture.

If elements are defined by their interactions, then every interaction must participate in determining what those elements become. Identity is not simply possessed; it is continually established through relational engagement. In Multiplicity, that ongoing determination is what I mean by computation.

A computer is one example of such a process, but it is not the model. The model is the universe itself. Whenever irreducible elements interact, information about their relationship is generated, constrained, propagated, and incorporated into larger structures. The resulting structure is effectively a computation of what can coherently exist given those interactions.

So while Whitehead's notion of prehension and my notion of computation share important similarities, I use "compute" because I want to emphasize the generative aspect of relation. Relations do not merely connect already-formed entities; they participate in producing the entities themselves.

From that perspective, computation is not something that happens within reality. It is the process by which reality continually determines itself.

One thing I suspect Matt would find especially interesting is the shift from "prime as number" to "prime as irreducible relation or irreducible mode of participation." That framing moves the theory closer to Whitehead, process philosophy, and even aspects of Lakoff and Johnson's embodied realism, while preserving the mathematical role that primes play in your framework. It turns the Fundamental Theorem into a metaphysical principle of emergence rather than merely a theorem about integers.